## 14. Limitations, Conclusions and Future Work


### 14.1 Limitations

- Source data quality is heterogeneous (missing coordinates/descriptions/types).
- Neo4j is a derived view of PostgreSQL and requires synchronization.
- Some analytics/ML features are demo-oriented and not production-optimized.

### 14.2 Conclusions

This project delivered an end-to-end data engineering platform for French tourism POIs, from ingestion to storage (PostgreSQL), graph projection (Neo4j), API exposure (FastAPI), and interactive analytics (Streamlit). The solution is reproducible via Docker Compose, observable through health/run-tracking endpoints, and deployable via Kubernetes (GitLab CI). The dashboard demonstrates key analytics workflows (KPIs, charts, map exploration) as well as an itinerary generator and a clustering extension for advanced exploration.


### 14.3 Future Work

- Improve incremental ETL by loading only POIs updated since the last successful run.
- Add automated API and pipeline tests (contract tests for responses, DB/Neo4j mocking).
- Add observability: structured logs, metrics, and tracing for ETL + API endpoints.
- Optimize heavy analytics endpoints with caching and/or pre-aggregations.
- Harden graph sync operations (permissions, idempotency guarantees, monitoring).

